    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Mid‑19th‑century shoreline settlement drew farmers and fishermen to Lake Erie Beach’s fertile lands and abundant fisheries.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lake_erie_beach_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Murphy family founded Lake Erie Beach Park in 1924, and it remains a public park today.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16,
        17,
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://lakeeriebeachpark.org/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The 1852 arrival of the railroad at Evans Station spurred development in the 1870s and 1890s, boosting connectivity.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lake_erie_beach_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Erie County and Lake Erie were named after the Erie tribe of Native Americans who lived there before 1654.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
